  "problem_type": "Statistical reasoning / base-rate fallacy — a case where a true fact is used to support an invalid inference by ignoring the exposure denominator",
  "strategy": "Denominator analysis: any claim about relative risk must be expressed as a rate (events per unit of exposure), not an absolute count or percentage of events. The socratic move is to ask: what is the denominator, and is it the same across the groups being compared?",
  "hardest_part": "The stat is true, which makes the fallacy seductive. The error is not in the data — it's in the inferential step. Distinguishing 'where attacks happen' (numerator frequency) from 'attack risk' (rate = numerator / denominator) requires resisting the surface-level plausibility of the conclusion.",
  "solution": "The conclusion is invalid. The logical error is **exposure bias / denominator neglect** — a form of the base rate fallacy. Here is the structure of the mistake:\n\n**The valid claim:** 90% of shark attacks occur in shallow water.\n\n**The hidden assumption in the conclusion:** That swimmers are equally distributed between shallow and deep water, so attack counts are proportional to attack risk.\n\n**Why that assumption fails:** Approximately 99%+ of all human swimming time occurs in shallow water. Deep-water swimming is rare, happens mostly among divers with specific equipment, and is logistically inaccessible to most people. Of course most attacks happen where almost all swimmers are — this tells us almost nothing about comparative risk per swimmer-hour.\n\n**Analogy that makes the error visible:** 'More car accidents happen on dry roads than icy roads — therefore icy roads are safer.' True in absolute counts; false as a risk claim because dry-road exposure vastly dominates.\n\n**What additional information is actually required:**\n1. Total swimmer-hours (or diver-hours) in shallow water vs. deep water.\n2. Attack rate per swimmer-hour in each zone — this is the only valid safety metric.\n3. A consistent operational definition of 'shallow' vs. 'deep' (the threshold matters).\n4. Whether the populations are comparable (recreational swimmers vs. technical divers have different behavior, equipment, and shark-encounter profiles).\n\n**The correct inferential standard:** If attacks-per-swimmer-hour in deep water is lower than in shallow water, the conclusion might hold. But given that very few people ever swim in deep open ocean, the 90% figure is almost entirely explained by exposure, not by differential shark behavior — and deep water almost certainly carries *higher* per-hour risk, not lower, since large pelagic sharks (oceanic whitetip, blue shark) inhabit open deep water precisely where rescuers cannot reach."
